(67, 1, '2020-03-11 13:16:23', '2020-03-11 13:16:23', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nThe SET command with no arguments will list all variables for the current command prompt session. Most of these varaiables will be system-wide environmental variables, like %PATH% or %TEMP%.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Screenshot of the SET command</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>NOTE: Calling SET will list all regular (static) variables for the current session. This listing excludes the dynamic environmental variables like %DATE% or %CD%. You can list these dynamic variables by viewing the end of the help text for SET, invoked by calling SET /?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://steve-jansen.github.io/guides/windows-batch-scripting/part-2-variables.html\">http://steve-jansen.github.io/guides/windows-batch-scripting/part-2-variables.html</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'List existing CMD variables', 'When writing a CMD script in Windows, you\'ll very likely need to know what variables does Windows provide by default. This command will help you figure it out.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'list-existing-cmd-variables', '', '', '2020-03-11 13:16:23', '2020-03-11 13:16:23', '', 0, 'http://mywebsite.test/?p=67', 0, 'post', '', 0),
